or search results is shown in the source image, which the knowledge file appropriately omits from its text description. For the sort section, there's a reference label and separator in the source that the knowledge file treats as a placeholder for the next section. I'm also noticing that the title about nbs:listSearchResult attributes appears to be inferred from context rather than explicitly stated in the source material. This seems like a reasonable interpretation.\n\nThe source describes a specific sequence: being on page 3 with 44 results, then selecting page 2 while the results simultaneously decrease to 10 items. The knowledge file's wording suggests the decrease happened first while still on page 3, then the page selection occurred—a subtle but meaningful difference in the order of events.\n\nLooking at the button state descriptions, I need to verify whether the knowledge file accurately captures what the source says about the navigation buttons' display conditions.\n\nThe source indicates that both 最初 (first page) and 前へ (previous page) appear as clickable links when you're on page 2, since both transitions are possible from that position. The knowledge file describes this as \"前ページへ遷移可能\" (can transition to previous page), which technically works for 前へ but is a bit narrow for 最初, which specifically means going to the first page. It's a minor distinction though.\n\nNow I'm looking at how the source organizes its content with multiple section headers, starting with 検索結果件数. I'm checking the RST structure more carefully now. The source has three distinct h2 sections marked with underlines (検索結果件数, ページング, 検索結果), but the knowledge file combines all of them into a single section. According to the validation rule, when the source has multiple h2 headings with substantial content and the knowledge file doesn't split them accordingly, this should be flagged as a structural mismatch. I'm checking whether the h3 rule applies here. The source has three h2 sections with