king the \"前へ\" button restores the pagination display to its normal state—it mentions the general paging behavior but misses this particular step in the scenario.\n\nSimilarly, the source includes a parenthetical note that re-searching from the form returns you to page 1, which is useful context for understanding the paging behavior, but this clarification isn't reflected in the knowledge file either. Both of these are minor omissions—they're informational details about the scenario flow rather than critical constraints that would affect implementation. So items 1 and 2 are really just scenario descriptions and clarifications rather than critical implementation constraints—they're the kind of thing that's obvious from context or parenthetical in the source. Item 1 about the \"前へ\" button restoring normal state and item 2 about re-searching returning to page 1 both fall into that category, so I'll mark them as minor omissions.\n\nFor the section structure, I need to reconsider how RST heading levels work. The document uses `====` for the top-level sections and `----` for subsections, which means `====` is actually h1 and `----` is h2. So the knowledge file should have 3 h2 sections, not merging them all into a single section. the knowledge file is showing me that the s2 section is essentially a placeholder pointing to the sort section that continues beyond this excerpt, so the actual content structure makes sense with the hierarchy I've identified.\n\nLooking at what's actually missing from the knowledge file compared to the source, I'm finding two minor gaps: the behavior describing how page number correspondence returns to normal after navigating from a reduced-results state, and a parenthetical note about what happens when you search again from the form. These are useful details for understanding the full user experience, though not critical for the core functionality documentation.\n\nNow checking the knowledge file's scenario description against the source more